               <p>JOSEPH SMITH. I am a <rs id="t18270531-307-viclabel1652" type="occupation">gun-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270531-307-victim1672 t18270531-307-viclabel1652"></join>. On the 13th of April I gave my son a pistol to take to Somers'-town; he returned in about twenty minutes without it, crying.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270531-307-person1673">
                  WILLIAM 
                  COLTON
               <interp inst="t18270531-307-person1673" type="surname" value="COLTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-307-person1673" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270531-307-person1673" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I received information, and went with the little boy, who pointed the prisoner out; I asked him where the pistol was; he denied it; I said I knew he had got it; he then said, "Say nothing about it, I will go, and give it to you;" he took me down Gray's-inn-lane, and gave it me from under several things; I have known him nine years; he behaved well; I believe he was in distress.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The boy held it up to several people; I thought he ought not to have such a thing, and took it from him.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18270531-307-verdict1653" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18270531-307-verdict1653" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 16.</p>
